Here's a complete migration guide. The original code has several constructs that are removed, broken, or obsolete in .NET 8.

## Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Construct | .NET 8 Status | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes on stop |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete, unreliable | Won't wake `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | Works, but has a **race condition** | Multiple enqueues, only one dequeue per signal |
| Raw `Thread` | Works, but unnecessary | `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>` are idiomatic |

## Race Condition in the Original

```
Thread A: Enqueue("a") → Set signal
Thread B: Enqueue("b") → Set signal  (signal already set — no-op)
Worker:   WaitOne → Reset → Dequeue("a") → handle
Worker:   WaitOne → BLOCKS FOREVER     ← "b" is stuck in queue
```

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — drain remaining items if desired
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();                       // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        try { await _workerTask; }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Key Migration Decisions

**`Channel<T>` replaces `Queue` + `ManualResetEvent` + `lock`**
— Thread-safe, backpressure-aware, and fixes the race condition. One type replaces three.

**`CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Abort/Interrupt`**
— Cooperative cancellation is the only supported model in .NET 8. `ReadAllAsync` checks the token on every iteration.

**`Task.Run` replaces `new Thread`**
— Uses the thread pool. For long-lived work, this is fine because `ReadAllAsync` yields the thread while awaiting items.

**`Channel.Writer.Complete()` enables graceful drain**
— The worker finishes processing queued items, then exits. The `CancellationToken` acts as a hard timeout if draining takes too long.

## If You Need a Synchronous API

Use `BlockingCollection<T>` instead:

```csharp
public class EventProcessorSync : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(() => RunLoop(_cts.Token));
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(ct))
                Handle(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();
        _cts?.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        _thread?.Join();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Quick Checklist

- ✅ Remove all `Thread.Abort()` calls — they **will** throw at runtime
- ✅ Replace `Thread.Interrupt()` with `CancellationToken`
- ✅ Replace `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` with `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>`
- ✅ Implement `IDisposable` / `IAsyncDisposable` for cleanup
- ✅ Audit for the multi-enqueue race condition (it was a latent bug)
